fields.name: Wookiepants
fields.story:
Wookiepants was brought to us after his previous owner passed away. They lived in a remote farmhouse, and Wookiepants was discovered living alone in the house,  for almost three weeks from the day his owner was rushed to the hospital, by a mailman dropping off some post.
The family of his owner were unable and unwilling to care for such a large dog, so that is how he ended up with us.
Wookiepants is an avid swimmer and can often be seen swimming in the pond on the compound. He is a certified water rescue dog and occasionally lends a paw when there's water rescuing to be done.

fields.name: Daisy
fields.story:
Daisy came to our sanctuary directly after being rescued from a puppy mill, she was suffering from severe anxiety issues and deformed paw pads.
Being surrounded by fellow buddies, and being patiently cared and nurtured by the folks here, Daisy slowly became comfortable in her environment. 
Daisy enjoys swimming and 'rescuing' water lilies from the pond.
Daisy works once a week at the nursing home as a comfort dog and a gigantic feet warmer.

fields.name: Rasputin
fields.story:
Rasputin was brought into a clinic to get a tumor on his neck removed, it was benign, but his owners didn't came back to pick him up.
He is a very quiet dog and would rather sit observing the happenings rather than partake in them.
Rasputin also prefers human companionship to that of his peers, so he is really nice company on walks or just hanging out on the compound.
He likes, you guessed it, long walks. He also likes carrots!

fields.name: Bernard
fields.story:
Bernard broke his hip a few years ago but it didn't heal very well. It was hard for his owners, who were both working full-time, to give him the exercise and care that he needed at that point so they brought him to us. 
Bernard was depressed for a long time and disinterested in everything that was going on. As time went by, with the freedom of being able to walk outside whenever he wanted and needed to, and the quiet persistence of Boss (who just wouldn't leave him alone), Bernard slowly emerged from under his dark cloud. He spent a year working as a comfort dog but the problems with his hip forced him into early retirement. He now spends his days just enjoying an idle existence!

fields.name: Boss
fields.story:
Boss came to us as a rescue from a puppy-mill when she was into early adulthood. By then she had already had two litters of puppies. Due to the poor living conditions that she was forced to endure, both her front paws have growth deformities.
Although Anatolian Shepherds are not know for being social creatures, Boss was trained and worked as a comfort dog to the elderly. Not only was she really good at her job, she was and still is one of the most popular visitor to the senior centre.
Boss is, as her name suggests, the leader of the pack here.

fields.name: Delta
fields.story:
We will never forget how we found Delta tied to the front gate of the sanctuary, in the middle of the night,  without so much as a note.
She was shaken and the ordeal left her fearful and refusing to look at anyone or let anyone close.
After several weeks of patient attempts to calm her down and gain her trust, we had a break through. Delta became best friends with Reggie and the two of them can be seen roaming the compound or just hanging out together by the apple tree.

fields.name: Humphrey
fields.story:
Humphrey came to The Buddy Clubhouse after three attempts at rehoming him by his owners failed. The family had downsized to a small apartment but Humphrey was too used to having so much space to roam that boredom drove him to some destructive behavior. 
He is fond of playing catch with a ball but because of his age we have stopped that completely. He was a former walking companion for the senior citizens at the Batista nursing home.
These days, Humphrey is enjoying his retirement just lazing in the shade.

fields.name: Lola
fields.story:
Lola is a rambunctious one! She had moved to four different homes prior to arriving at The Buddy Clubhouse. We knew immediately that we needed to keep her busy so she started basic training the next day. Lola is a fantastic swimmer, we believe that she is half seal!
She excels in water sport, retrieving being her specialty, and she is undergoing training for water rescue.

fields.name: Mala
fields.story:
We brought Mala in as a puppy who was prone to epileptic seizures. A combination therapy of modern and homeopathic medication has, thankfully, kept these seizures at bay.
With her troubles under control, Mala is living life to the fullest!
She trains regularly with a skijoring team and enjoys competing in agility courses. She is also a comfort dog to young children at the long term patient pediatric ward in the local hospital.

fields.name: Nomad
fields.story:
Our resident troublemaker! Nomad is more puppy than the senior he is. He is always up to mischief and had to be rescued from some really unimaginable situations.
He is an affectionate fella and often brings home bounty(dead mice and fish) to feed the family. During his hay-days, Nomad was a brute of a musher. Now he's just digging holes and pretending to be a rabbit.

fields.name: Ollie
fields.story:
Ollie was a farm dog, so it was near impossible to get her into any training programs. We had to start from zero with basic commandos and went from there. 
Two years after she arrived at The Buddy Clubhouse, she (surprisingly) competed in her first agility competition and did really well.
She is now retired and just enjoys life herding her friends around the compound.

fields.name: Reggie
fields.story:
Reggie loves to walk! So it's no surprise that he's a regular hiking companion to the senior citizens at the local senior hikers club.
He was brought to the sanctuary by a friend whose living situation changed and had to be forced to give up his giant field.
Reggie still sees his owner from time to time as his owner volunteers alot of his free time to helping out at the sanctuary.

fields.name: Ruth
fields.story:
Ruth was found living in a forest by hikers. Her fur was completely matted and she was suffering from malnutrition and mange. 
She required a period of intensive rehabilitation as she had started to become a little feral. She was prone to defensive aggression so needed to be regularly evaluated and after we managed to put some bulk on her, she started behavioral correction training.
Ruth is a fierce competitor in agilty games for large/giant breed class. Ruth doesn't like water so you'll never find her near the pond here.

fields.name: Soren
fields.story:
Soren is a little smaller than your average Leonberger, he is a jovial fella and a food thief. 
He's a walking companion in a walking program for people with special needs. Soren is very patient with people, especially with the little ones and is training to be certified as a comfort dog.

fields.name: Toga
fields.story:
Toga was, together with her two siblings, rescued from a puppy mill. Her siblings have since passed on. 
For a dog of her size and breed to live this long is a truly respectable feat. 
She was a hiker up until 2019 when arthritis in her joints forced her to stop. Age and the physical limitations on her has made her rather grumpy and less patient with the other buddies. 
Ruth considers herself a laptop and would try to climb onto any available lap she sees.

fields.name: Alpha
fields.description: Contribute just because you care and want to make a difference in the lives of these wonderful creatures who can bring so much joy to many

fields.name: Epsilon
fields.description: Contribute towards some creature comforts for the buddies - e.g. new cushion or leash when the current one wears out or breaks

fields.name: Gamma
fields.description: Contribute towards some yummies for the buddies - this goes towards reward snacks after a training day

fields.name: Kappa
fields.description: Contribute to send the buddies on sporting events like agility, mushing/skijoring and water-sport competitions that require an enrollment fee

fields.name: Omega
fields.description: Contribute towards medical expenses for the senior buddies who need extra attention, aid and medication to sustain a good quality life

fields.name: Sigma
fields.description: Contribute towards sending the buddies on training e.g. comfort dog and commando training, water-rescue and retrieving training, mushing/skijoring training, agility and fitness training
